An earlier exposition of the same nature as Gerry's source is Leslie Gelb's &quot;The Irony of Vietnam:  The System Worked&quot;.  Gelb is the guy who put together the Pentagon Papers (not the guy who gave 'em to the NY Times).  In his book (there's a co-author, but I can't remember his name), Gelb basically states that Presidents from Kennedy on (maybe even Eisenhower) were caught in a bind:  we'd declared a non-communist Vietnam &quot;vital&quot; to our national security and any backing away from that would be seen as &quot;soft on communism&quot;  On the other hand, going all out to &quot;win&quot; would've been loudly protested by the &quot;liberals&quot;, to say nothing of the possible risk of a wider war (WWIII?).  Thus, we were stuck in a &quot;no-win&quot; situation.  It makes a lot of sense to me.
